INSTALL — import_pentacam
=========================

Prerequisites (Linux)
---------------------

- Rust toolchain (install via https://rustup.rs)
- Linux x86_64 (Ubuntu 22.04+ or equivalent, glibc >= 2.35)
- curl (for downloading dependencies)
- Internet connection (first build only — downloads ONNX Runtime and OCR models)
- Optional: NVIDIA GPU with CUDA drivers for GPU acceleration

Prerequisites (Windows)
-----------------------

- Rust toolchain (install via https://rustup.rs — uses MSVC toolchain by default)
- Git for Windows (https://git-scm.com — includes Git Bash)
- Visual Studio Build Tools (https://visualstudio.microsoft.com/downloads/)
  with "Desktop development with C++" workload
- LLVM (needed for MuPDF FFI binding generation via bindgen).
  ./configure will auto-download libclang.dll (~96 MB, extracted from the
  ~936 MB LLVM release archive) into a local llvm/ directory if not found.
  No admin privileges required. Alternatively, install LLVM system-wide from
  https://github.com/llvm/llvm-project/releases before running ./configure.
- curl, tar, xz (bundled with Git Bash)
- Internet connection (first build only — downloads ONNX Runtime, OCR models,
  and libclang if not already installed)
- Optional: NVIDIA GPU with CUDA drivers for GPU acceleration

Quick Start (Linux)
-------------------

    ./configure
    make install

This will:
1. Download ONNX Runtime (GPU version if CUDA is detected, CPU otherwise)
2. Download PaddleOCR v5 models (~100 MB)
3. Build the release binary
4. Install to ~/.local/lib/import_pentacam/ with a wrapper in ~/.local/bin/

After installation, run:

    import_pentacam --help

Quick Start (Windows)
---------------------

Open Git Bash:

    ./configure --cpu-only       # or omit --cpu-only if you have an NVIDIA GPU
    make dist

This will:
1. Detect Windows and download the correct ONNX Runtime (win-x64 .zip)
2. Download PaddleOCR v5 models (~100 MB)
3. Detect LLVM/libclang for MuPDF binding generation
4. Build the release binary (.exe)
5. Assemble dist/import_pentacam/ with .exe, .dll, and models

After building, test:

    cd dist/import_pentacam
    ./import_pentacam.exe --help

Note: `make` may not be installed in Git Bash by default. If not, you can
build manually:

    # After running ./configure, extract variables from config.mk:
    ORT_DIR=$(grep '^ORT_DIR' config.mk | sed 's/.*:= //')
    export ORT_LIB_LOCATION="$ORT_DIR/lib"
    export ORT_PREFER_DYNAMIC_LINK=1
    export LIBCLANG_PATH="C:/Program Files/LLVM/bin"   # adjust if installed elsewhere
    cargo build --release

Then assemble the distribution folder:

    mkdir -p dist/import_pentacam/models
    cp target/release/import_pentacam.exe dist/import_pentacam/
    cp "$ORT_DIR"/lib/onnxruntime.dll dist/import_pentacam/
    cp models/*.onnx models/*.txt dist/import_pentacam/models/

Configure Options
-----------------

    ./configure                    Auto-detect everything
    ./configure --cpu-only         Force CPU-only build (no CUDA, smaller download)
    ./configure --ort-dir DIR      Use an existing ONNX Runtime installation
    ./configure --prefix DIR       Install to DIR instead of ~/.local

The configure script works identically on Linux and Windows (Git Bash). On
Windows it automatically:
- Downloads the win-x64 ORT package (.zip) instead of linux-x64 (.tgz)
- Detects MSVC (cl.exe) and CMake availability
- Locates LLVM/libclang and writes LIBCLANG_PATH to config.mk

Make Targets
------------

    make                Build release binary only
    make dist           Build + assemble dist/import_pentacam/ with all
                        libraries and models (portable, self-contained)
    make dist-tar       Build + create archive (.tar.gz on Linux, .zip on Windows)
    make deb            Build + create .deb package (Linux only)
    make install        Build + install to PREFIX (default: ~/.local)
    make clean          Remove build artifacts

Distributing (Linux)
--------------------

After `make dist`, the dist/import_pentacam/ folder is fully self-contained.
Copy it to any Linux x86_64 machine and run directly — no installation or
environment variables needed:

    cd import_pentacam/
    ./import_pentacam --help

For GPU support, the target machine needs NVIDIA CUDA drivers installed
(the CUDA runtime libraries are bundled).

Distributing (Windows)
----------------------

After `make dist`, the dist/import_pentacam/ folder contains:

    import_pentacam.exe
    onnxruntime.dll
    models/
      pp-ocrv5_server_det.onnx
      en_pp-ocrv5_mobile_rec.onnx
      en_ppocrv5_dict.txt

Copy this folder to any Windows x86_64 machine. Windows automatically finds
DLLs next to the .exe — no PATH or environment configuration needed.

For GPU builds, onnxruntime_providers_cuda.dll and
onnxruntime_providers_shared.dll are also included.

System-wide Installation (Linux, as root)
-----------------------------------------

    ./configure --prefix /usr/local
    sudo make install

This installs to /usr/local/lib/import_pentacam/ with a wrapper script
in /usr/local/bin/.

MuPDF Patch (Windows)
---------------------

The mupdf crate (v0.6) has a build issue on Windows: bindgen does not
generate the `max_align_t` type from MSVC headers. This repo includes a
patched copy in patches/mupdf-0.6.0/ that provides a Windows-only stand-in.
The patch is applied via [patch.crates-io] in Cargo.toml and has no effect
on Linux builds (gated behind #[cfg(windows)]).

Notes
-----

- ONNX Runtime is downloaded to ort/ in the source directory. OCR models
  are downloaded to models/. Both are preserved across clean builds.
- On Linux, the binary uses RUNPATH=$ORIGIN to find its shared libraries
  relative to itself. No LD_LIBRARY_PATH configuration is needed.
- On Windows, DLLs next to the .exe are found automatically by the OS.
- OCR models and ONNX Runtime libraries must be in the same relative
  location as the binary (models/ subdirectory, .so/.dll files alongside).
- GPU memory: expect ~8-34 GB VRAM usage during OCR. The software falls
  back to CPU if GPU is unavailable or runs out of memory.
